properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Dewhurst, Emerald.
  • There is a grassfire at Beaconsfield-Emerald Road, Emerald that is under control.
  • Firefighters will remain on scene overnight.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 3:40pm. 
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do:
  • Keep the roads clear so emergency services can respond.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority. 

The next update is expected by 15/09/2025 11:50 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Coongulla, Monomak.
  • This Advice replaces the Advice issued at 2:26pm Monday 15 September.
  • There is a bushfire at Beaver Meadows Track that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is travelling from Beaver Meadows Track in a southerly direction towards Coongulla.
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and plan for what you will do if the situation changes. 
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Firefighters are responding to this fire. 
  • Heavy machinery is operating in the area. 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 16/09/2025 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for Diamond Creek, Wattle Glen.
  • There are waste materials on fire in the vicinity of Black Gully Road and Broad Gully Road, Diamond Creek.
  • The fire is under control.
  • You may see or smell smoke in the area until Tuesday morning, 16 September.
  • Emergency services are aware of this incident.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.name: Community Information
properties.location: Porepunkah and surrounding areas including Myrtleford and Bright
properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for the incident at Porepunkah and surrounding areas including Myrtleford and Bright.
  • Victoria Police advises the search for armed offender Desmond Freeman (Filby) continues. 
  • To support this, the Mount Buffalo National Park will remain closed for a further period of time. We will advise when this is no longer the case. 
  • Given the extensive searches undertaken since 26 August, the advice to avoid travelling to Porepunkah has been lifted. 
  • Victoria Police advises those in the area to remain vigilant and report any suspicious behaviour to Triple Zero (000) or Crimestoppers on 1800 333 000. 
This Community Information replaces the following:
  • The Advice issued at 3:46 pm Saturday, 13 September.
  • The Community Information issued at 3:45 pm Saturday, 13 September.
If you see Desmond Freeman (Filby), call 000 immediately and do not approach the offender. 
What you should do:
  • If you are in the Porepunkah area, you must follow instructions of emergency services at the scene.
  • Anyone who witnessed the incident or has any information is asked to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000 or www.crimestoppers.com.au.
Impacts in your area:
  • Road closures may change at short notice. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website for updates on road closures: traffic.transport.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by Victoria Police.

The next update is expected by 21/09/2025 10:40 am or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency app
  • VicEmergency Facebook or Twitter
  • Victoria Police Facebook or Twitter
  • For more information, visit: Victoria Police - Porepunkah incident
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment, contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Severe Weather Warning for DAMAGING WINDS
properties.webHeadline:
DAMAGING WINDS averaging 60 to 70 km/h with peak gusts around 100 km/h are expected to continue today and into Tuesday. Peak gusts about the alpine peaks may reach around 110 km/h late tonight and early Tuesday morning. Winds are expected to ease late Tuesday morning.
Locations which may be affected ...
